description: The group makes preparations for the walk.
Stop at Gateway Heritage Plaza with more preparation talk.
Boyce remembers the development of I-40 in the 1960s.
Boyce Talks Aside About Presidential Candidate Donald J. Trump.
Washington and Boyce Remember The Black Diamond Club.
Talk Briefly About Elks Lodge and The Club Baron.
Washington and Boyce Describe Jefferson Street's Heyday Compared to Today.
Stop at Elks Lodge formerly Club Baron.
Boyce Remembers Playing at Club Baron and Jimi Hendrix.
Washington Remembers Club Baron, Gambling and Herbert Hunter.
Washington and Boyce recall Mayor Ben West's "clean up" of Jefferson St., the interstate, and the clubs forced to move downtown.
Washington and Boyce recall Joel Rattenberg booker for The Jail nightclub.
Washington and Boyce discuss Jefferson St. real estate.
Stop at Jefferson Street Missionary Baptist Church.
Boyce discusses how traffic changed and how that affected the neighborhood.
Boyce and Connor discuss the film Straight Outta Compton.
Stop at Alkebu-Lan Images Book Store.
Boyce discusses his children, his grandsons, and raising children on the books sold at Alkebu-Lan Images Book Store.
Washington and others discuss a now closed community outdoor swimming pool.
Boyce briefly discusses Prices club on Jefferson St.
Boyce and Hostetler discuss presenting information to the Mayor of Nashville, and how Hostetler's Human Geography class/Pearl Cohn High School could help.
Ingrid Fletcher leaves.
Boyce touches base with Connor and introduces him to other group members.
Boyce and Connor discuss their future plans.
Boyce talks about where he grew up and how he came to Nashville.
Boyce catches up with his friend Joe outside Seafood Sensations, discuss Bishop Joseph Walker III.
Stop at College Crib.
Boyce's Camera is shut off.
Boyce and Shapiro discuss street fairs and TSU's Homecoming.
Boyce and Shapiro discuss playing guitar and recording music.
Boyce expresses his desire for an open space/park on Jefferson St.
Boyce cleans Shapiro's shirt.
The group prepares for the next part of the walk.
Connor and Boyce discuss the mural at Gateway Heritage Plaza.
Boyce drives with Shapiro, Washington and Connor to the next location.
Boyce talks with an artist he wants to work with over the phone.
Connor and Boyce discuss the police, and Connor tells stories about police interactions.
Boyce stops at New Covenant Christian Church (Disciples of Christ).
Connor tells another story about a police interaction he had, and comments on police incidents in the news.
Connor and Boyce rejoin group at Woodcuts Gallery & Framing.
Connor and Boyce talk about one of their neighbors.
Boyce reconnects with his former neighbor, and the owner of Woodcuts, Nate Harris.
Harris shows art pieces of Greg Ridley, Ludie Amos, Terry and Jerry Lynn to the group from the gallery.
Washington talks about the Good Jelly Jones Club.
Preparations are made for the next part of the walk.
Connor talks about injuries sustained from an old accident.
Connor and Boyce discuss traffic across Nashville, Germantown, and the development of Jefferson St.
Group drives back to Jefferson Street Sound, Boyce and Connors talk about cars, Sirius XM, and Boyce's website.
Group has a conversation about next steps in the project and end the walk at Jefferson Street Sound.
